06164nam a22012015i 9780691189048DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2019038113  a97806911890487 a10.1515/97806911890482doi  a(DE-B1597)541385  a(OCoLC)1130387746  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ00aRS67.C6bB53 2020 4aRS67.C6bB53 2020 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a615.109512231 aBian, He, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKnow Your Remedies :bPharmacy and Culture in Early Modern China /cHe Bian. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2020  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b9 b/w illus. 3 tables. 4 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPART I -- tPART II -- tEpilogue -- tAppendixes -- tChinese Character Glossary -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA cultural history of the concept of pharmacy, both the material nature of drugs and the trade in medicine, in early modern China Know Your Remedies presents a panoramic inquiry into China's early modern cultural transformation through the lens of pharmacy. In the history of science and civilization in China, pharmacy-as a commercial enterprise and as a branch of classical medicine-resists easy characterization. While China's long tradition of documenting the natural world through state-commissioned pharmacopeias, known as bencao, dwindled after the sixteenth century, the ubiquitous presence of Chinese pharmacy shops around the world today testifies to the vitality of Traditional Chinese Medicine. Rejecting narratives of intellectual stagnation or an unchanging folk culture, He Bian argues that pharmacy's history in early modern China can best be understood as a dynamic interplay between elite and popular culture.Beginning with decentralizing trends in book culture and fiscal policy in the sixteenth century, Bian reveals pharmacy's central role in late Ming public discourse. Fueled by factional politics in the early 1600s, amateur investigation into pharmacology reached peak popularity among the literati on the eve of the Qing conquest in the mid-seventeenth century. The eighteenth century witnessed a systematic reclassification of knowledge, as the Qing court turned away from pharmacopeia in favor of a demedicalized natural history. Throughout this time, growth in long-distance trade enabled the rise of urban pharmacy shops, generating new knowledge about the natural world.Bringing together a wealth of primary sources, Know Your Remedies makes an essential contribution to the study of Chinese history and the history of medicine.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aMedicine, ChinesexHistory. 0aPharmacopoeiaszChinaxHistory. 0aPharmacyzChinaxHistory. 0aTransmission of textszChinaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aChinese history.  aChinese letter.  aFang'an.  aLi Shizhen.  aLiu Wentai.  aMateria Medica.  aSinologist.  aSinology.  aThe Monkey and the Inkpot: Natural History and Its Transformations in Early Modern China.  aZhang Yu.  aZhao Xuemin.  aZhu Youcheng.  aapothecaries.  aapothecary.  adrugs.  afolk culture.  agazetteers.  aguilds.  aherbal.  aherbs.  ahistory of science.  amaterial culture.  amedicalized.  amedication.  amedicinal.  amodernity.  anatural history.  apharmaceutical.  apharmacist.  aphysicians.  aplants.  aprescriptions.  aprint culture.  asubstances.  atradition.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe Gr